Electrical source imaging (ESI) is a technique that reconstructs brain or cardiac electrical activity from electrical potentials measured away from the brain or heart. 

It's a noninvasive technique that uses mathematical algorithms to localize the source of a given scalp EEG.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

**ESI estimates the cortical generator of the electroencephalography (EEG) signals recorded with scalp electrodes.** 

**It involves modeling brain electrical activity as a series of equivalent current source distributions.**



ESI is used to **localize the activated brain regions by incorporating temporal and spatial components**. It's been consistently implemented over the recent years to elucidate complex brain operations.
